   Genes & Cells

     * [crop]
       News in Brief: Coelacanth is not closest fishy relative of terrestrial animals
       Genes of "living fossil" do reveal changes needed to live on dry land.
       Peter Scoones/Getty Images
     * News in Brief: New bird flu claims more victims
       H7N9 influenza spreads to Beijing, may come from poultry and pigeons.
     * New flu in China reveals its avian origins
       H7N9 influenza genes came from three bird viruses.
     * New technique gives see-through view into mouse brains
       Replacing fatty molecules turns organs transparent, allowing study of structure and function at the same time.
     * Molecule in meat may increase heart disease risk
       Gut bacteria transform compound into artery hardener.
     * Light found in cocaine addiction tunnel
       Using lasers, scientists target a sluggish set of neurons in rats to ease drug compulsion.
     * Biological transistor built for living computers
       DNA-based switches could be used in diagnosis and treatment of diseases.
     * Eye drops reduce signs of macular degeneration in mice
       Targeting cholesterol in retina stops rogue blood vessel growth often seen in the vision disease.
     * Gut microbes may be behind weight loss after gastric bypass
       Mice slim down after receiving bacteria transplanted from rodents that had the surgery.
     * News in Brief: Longhorn cattle ancestors came from Pakistan
       New World breeds trace back to both major bovine lineages, genetic analysis shows.
     * Giant squid population is one big happy species
       Elusive deep ocean dwellers have low genetic diversity despite living around the globe.
     * News in Brief: Bedbugs raise genetic defense against pesticides
       Bedbugs turn on several genes, in both their shells and their nerve cells, to stave off effects of insecticides.
     * News in Brief: New virus uses protein handle to infect cells
       Deadly coronavirus related to SARS attaches to protein on cells unlike the one SARS uses.
     * Tasmanian devil disease reveals its secrets
       The contagious cancer evades the animal's immune system by turning off key genes.
     * Alga borrows genes to beat the heat, acid and toxic metals
       Such genetic theft from bacteria and archaea is unusual among eukaryotes.
     * Mice get brain boost from transplanted human tissue
       An experimental transplant of what have long been considered just support cells shows they may play a role in memory and learning.
     * News in Brief: Missing link in taste chain identified
       Taste-cell protein sends message to brain that tongue has detected sweet, bitter or umami flavor.
     * Sperm swim against the current
       Human and mouse sperm both follow upstream currents to the egg.
     * Scientists race to understand deadly new virus
       Emerging virus causes severe illness, but doesn't spread as quickly as SARS.
     * News in Brief: Sleep loss affects gene activity
       Losing zzz's shifts workings of more than 700 genes.
     * Insulin levels wax and wane daily
       Modern life may clash with the hormone's natural cycle, new mouse research suggests.
     * News in Brief: Synthetic nanomaterial can recognize viruses
       The new method may have advantages over antibody-based technologies.
     * Imaging technique offers look inside hearing loss
       Two-photon microscopy visualizes hair cells in the inner ear, offering insights into processes leading to deafness.
     * Bird, human tweets come from similar parts of the brain
       Genetics study finds parallels in birdsong and language.
     * News in Brief: Bitter and sour taste detectors also say, 'too salty'
       Mice that can't sense the two tastes find high sodium attractive.
     * In research, it matters whether you're a man or a mouse
       A study that compares trauma responses of mice with those in people questions the relevance of mouse research to human disease.
     * Inflammation feeds E. coli
       Inflammation, normally a defense against microbes, may become counterproductive in the gut by feeding disease-causing bacteria.
     * News in Brief: Nerve stem cells treat gut disorder in mice
       Nerve stem cell therapy treats gut disorder by connecting to nervous system.
     * News in Brief: As fish watch prey, researchers watch fish's brains
       Genetically engineered neurons allow researchers to watch fish brains as they track prey.
     * Pigeons' prominent plumage traces to one gene
       A mutation responsible for ruffs, crests and collars appears to have arisen once and then passed among species through breeding.

